Believer Music Video! Sung by the Fun Squad (Imagine Dragons Cover) Fun Squad Family and the @ImagineDragons charity, TRF @trfdotorg, team up to share the fight against pediatric cancer through the eyes of a survivor.  The story is uniquely told through music video, as the Fun Squad Family musician teens, Jack, Jazzy and Kade Skye, sing a cover of the Imagine Dragonsâ€™ song, Believer in a captivating depiction of real-life courage and bravery, Averi of @OurFantasticFive .

OUR GOAL: Help us raise $100K for kids with cancer and hit 5M views of AWARENESS for TRF! What can you do? SHARE THE VIDEO and DONATE! The mission of TRF is to strengthen families financially and emotionally as they cope with the tragedy of a pediatric cancer diagnosis by offsetting out-of-pocket life expenses. Find out more at TRF.org or https://www.youtube.com/@TylerRobinsonFoundation

Title: Sabrina Carpenter: Tiny Desk Concert
Description:
Ashley Pointer | December 20, 2024
When I greeted Sabrina Carpenter at NPR HQ for her Tiny Desk debut, her charm was immediately disarming. Bubbling with excitement, she extended her hand, introduced herself and complimented my outfit with genuine warmth. Youâ€™d think this was one of her first â€œbig timeâ€ gigs, not a regular performance for a pop veteran, having sold out arenas across the country touring her now six time Grammy-nominated sixth album, Short nâ€™ Sweet. That humility made me love her even more. 

But Carpenter delivers far more than just charm in this performance. Backed by her band, complimented with pedal steel and a string quartet, she reimagines her biggest hits from Short nâ€™ Sweet, while sharing the stories in between songs of how these tracks came to life. Opening with â€œTaste,â€ strings serve up some playful pizzicato, before Carpenter and her band move into a lush, soulful version â€œBed Chem.â€ Then everyone swaps their electric instruments for acoustic to perform â€œPlease Please Pleaseâ€ and â€œSlim Pickins.â€ Finally, Carpenter closes with the viral favorite â€œJuno,â€ cheekily asking the audience, â€œHave you ever tried this one?â€ before sweeping her rear end across the windchimes, earning a laugh from the room. 

â€œWhen I first started [writing songs] it was kinda in a room like this â€” a room with very dry walls and thereâ€™s no reverb,â€ Carpenter reflects at the top of her performance. â€œBut thereâ€™s something so real and special.â€ That authenticity set the tone for a memorable session with one of 2024â€™s biggest breakout superstars.

About Kes:
Of the many musical acts which call Trinidad & Tobago home, perhaps none embody its polyglot culture more than KES, the eclectic soca outfit behind some of modern Caribbean musicâ€™s most indelible anthems. Celebrated for Carnival hits (â€œWotless,â€ â€œSavannah Grassâ€) and island pop jams (â€œTuesday on the Rocks,â€ â€œEndless Summerâ€), the band has brought Trinidad to the world, sharing stages with the likes of Will Smith, Major Lazer and John Legend. For the group â€” charismatic singer Kees Dieffenthaler (aka KES) and his brothers Jon (guitar) and Hans (drums), along with childhood friend, Riad Boochoon (bass) â€”blending soca, pop, rock, reggae, calypso, dancehall and afrobeats together is one part of their greater calling: To spread good vibes. The last three years have proven to be the most successful in the bandâ€™s decade-plus-run. â€œHello,â€ a fusion of afrobeats and soca originally released in 2017, continues to reach new audiences over two years after its release. With over 40 million plays on YouTube alone, it is one of the most streamed soca songs of all time. We Home, a live project recorded during the Covid-19 quarantine, is the bandâ€™s first album in over five years, with fresh renditions of KESâ€™ carnival classics showcasing their prowess as a live band par excellence.

Reporter:
 LED ZEPPELIN'S ROAD MANAGER
 SAYS HE PUT THE MONEY
 IN THE DEPOSIT BOX
 AND WHEN HE WENT BACK,
 IT WAS ALL GONE.
 THE POLICE
 SAY THERE WAS MONEY IN THE BOX,
 BUT THEY CAN'T TELL
 EXACTLY HOW MUCH.
 THE GROUP'S MANAGER,
 PETER GRANT,
 DISCUSSED THE THEFT
 AT A NEWS CONFERENCE TODAY.
IT WAS BROUGHT BACK
BY OUR ATTORNEY,
PHYSICALLY CARRIED,
BECAUSE THAT'S HIS FUNCTION.
WHEN HE COMES BACK, IT'S PUT
INTO A SAFE DEPOSIT BOX.
 POLICE SAID
 THEY WERE QUESTIONING ANYONE
 WHO HAD ACCESS
 TO THE SAFE DEPOSIT BOX,
 BUT THAT'S ABOUT ALL
 THEY WOULD SAY.
THE MONEY IS REPORTEDLY
THE LARGEST AMOUNT EVER TAKEN
FROM A HOTEL SAFE DEPOSIT BOX
IN NEW YORK CITY.
WE ASCERTAINED
THERE WAS MONEY IN THAT BOX
BY ONE OF THE CLERKS.
HE NOTED
ONE OF THE TRANSACTIONS.
TODAY WAS A LEAVING DAY ANYHOW.
SO, WE HAD THAT AMOUNT OF MONEY
BECAUSE WE HAD TO PAY OFF
AIRPLANES AND HOTELS.
AFTER HE MET WITH NEWSMEN,
